Bái mesca mór for Ulto fecht n-and i nSliab Fúait.
Docuridar didiu immarbága móra combara etroóu .i.e. Chonall ocus Coinculaind ocus Lóegaire.

Tucaid dam-sa ar Conall “inchind Me[i]ssgegra co ro-acilliur ócu na comram.” Ba bés d’ Ultaib ind inbaid sin cach curaid nomarbdais áel airthib con ndénad líathróite crúade díb. Ocus intan nobítis i n-immarbáig nó chomramaí.

column4: English translation here: Maith, a Connacht, the Gaelic Irish sentence translated to English as:  “The Isle belongs unto him in death - his family name is Galway – Kerry County Military Service Family History”  The original sentences contain an error where 'Conall' should be replaced by '-Cynow Castle'. Thereby the final translation of those medieval irish words are :  “Is Fir Cinnickson” , ar Conalllonae. (sic) “His Gaelic Irish family name belongs to him in death, his wife and children’s names go down hill; Galway County Military Service Family History”  And -  is fir conny - county Castle Irish Gaelic Army Barracks Services Families Histories  Conall means :  “Son of Conally King” Or,  “A Concave face”.  -  It may be difficult to determine the exact meaning due to a lack of context, as you would expect from reading Irish sentences.  - A Concave Face (meaning 'concavus') and Ireland’s Gaelic Military Army Barracks Services Family Histories are not necessarily mutually exclusive in Celtic languages. The most plausible English translation for this sentence is :  “The Isle belongs unto him with ‘Conally King’ County Castle family members names going down hill; Galway Counties military service Families History - barracks services families historians””  - The Irish Gaelic Military Army Barracks Services Family Histories (Irish county)-Military Service Families-(Barracks Services)-Family Histories-[names] are not necessarily mutually exclusive in Celtic Languages.
